Comment: c'est un programme intéressant

First: From your statement, the numerator can be 9^9, the denominator can be equal to it and can't be 9^9 on its own, which might be a typo or a flaw in your statement.

From your Statement, a fraction with 0 as denominator could be given (both numerator and denominator would be 0). From a programming perspective, it still works, however that can't happen in math. 

I don't really see why numerator has to be smaller or equal to the denominator. If you state that 0 <= numerator <= 9^9 and 0 < denominator <= 9^9, personally that feels better to me. 

I think it would be interesting to add some negative numbers as well, forcing clashers  without gdc to use the Euclidean algorithm (with division, not substraction) over some bruteforce for loops. 

Overall, I like the contribution and will most likely Approve it.

✅ Approved the contribution.
Comment: This puzzle is a good way to introduce shortcuts like gcd to players
Well Written

Python has a handy fractions.Fraction function that takes two integers and returns a Fraction object in the format specified in your output. Maybe just adding a space before and after the "/" will make it a little harder to use fractions.Fraction and even the playing field a little.
